scle spasticity","Bipolar disorder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary indication for gabapentinoids is \u003Cstrong\u003Eneuropathic pain\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly conditions such as diabetic peripheral neuropathy and post-herpetic neuralgia. These medications are considered first-line treatments for these conditions. While gabapentinoids are also approved for use in focal epilepsy, their primary clinical utility is in the management of neuropathic pain conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E may occasionally involve gabapentinoids; however, other medications like beta blockers or anticonvulsants are preferred first-line agents. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEssential tremor\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily treated with beta blockers and primidone. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscle spasticity\u003C/strong\u003E, baclofen and dantrolene are more appropriate first-line choices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Ebipolar disorder\u003C/strong\u003E, mood stabilisers like lithium and antipsychotics are the primary treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gabapentinoids are first-line treatments for neuropathic pain conditions like diabetic neuropathy and post-herpetic neuralgia.","Gabapentinoids are also indicated as adjunctive therapy for focal epilepsy.","Gabapentinoids are effective for anxiety disorders but this is not a licensed indication in most jurisdictions."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51781"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16685"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51781"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T18:54:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T12:51:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9376"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66332"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},